<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-711-156  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 711 156.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  August 6 1990 n312 p16(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A look at the cable debate. (telephone companies and cablecompanies contend for chance to sell cable services) (Perspective)(column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brotman, Stuart.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The telecommunications network community can participate in thedebate between telephone companies and cable television servicevendors by trying to view the situation from economic, regulatory,technological and policy perspectives.andP;  Network users and vendorscan perhaps achieve a clear view of the struggle over which groupor groups will profit from broadband fiber optic development andnew cable services.andP;  Network community members can analyze thestruggle because of their own experience with fiber optictechnology, costs and profit margins, and federal and stateregulatory practices.andP;  The best resolution of the debate may comefrom a varied, 'interdisciplinary' analysis.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Cable TVTelephone CompaniesCompetitionCommunications Service SuppliersNetworksFiber OpticsBroadbandGovernment Regulation.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>